{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1784141427,"nonce":"ezDVnu66uBfFncCIijICLw77xxI=","kind":"spec","title":"Quarantine review — flagged writes held for human approval (design)"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1784141427,"nonce":"GjDasDRtZjuicHOfEjM9+tN3w9Q=","body":"# Quarantine review — flagged writes held for human approval (design)\n\nStatus: design approved 2026-07-15 (Trevor), decomposed into 3 sub-projects.\nSupersedes the refuse-and-preserve + human-only-force secret policy shipped this\nsession (commits 4e4aa73 / 8239667 on branch feat/cockpit-tui-b1).\n\n## Problem\n\nThe write-boundary secret scan (internal/entryguard + internal/commentguard)\nrefuses a body that trips betterleaks on a syncable tier. But legitimate content\nroutinely trips it: test fixtures, docs that quote a token shape, code examples.\nAn agent then has no path — it cannot --force (human-only) and cannot rotate a\nfixture. Hard-refuse blocks real work; a blanket bypass would let real secrets\nthrough. We want a single gate that holds flagged content for explicit human\nreview, identically for human, script, and LLM writers, losing no work.\n\n## Locked decisions (Trevor, 2026-07-15)\n\n1. Flagged content is DIVERTED to holding, promoted on approval — it never\n   touches a syncable ref before a human signs off.\n2. Quarantine holds OPERATIONS, not entries. The live entry stays syncable and\n   untouched; the flagged op is parked and replayed on approval. New-entry,\n   update, patch, and comment all reduce to \"a flagged op held pending approval\".\n3. Holding lives in a new reserved `quarantine` namespace: private-typed\n   (non-syncable by construction), hidden from normal listings.\n4. One uniform gate for human/script/LLM. `--force` is redefined from\n   \"bypass the scan\" to \"approve my own quarantined write now\" (create + approve\n   atomically, human/CLI only). MCP has no force — an LLM write always parks.\n5. Review is a question-comment thread; approval is an explicit action\n   (`kref quarantine approve|reject \u003cid\u003e`), because a review can resolve\n   NEGATIVE — resolving the thread is not itself the decision.\n6. The review thread is anchored IN-CONTEXT to the target entry. For an update/\n   patch/comment on a live entry, the thread is on that entry. For a new entry,\n   the thread is on the draft (which becomes the entry on approval).\n\n## Model\n\nA quarantine item is an entry in the `quarantine` namespace, so it is already\naddressable, comment-able, and provenance-bearing (no new object type). It holds:\n\n- the parked op(s) — the SetBody / AddComment payload;\n- the target — either `new` plus intended tier/kind/title, or an existing\n  entry id (+ the op kind);\n- the findings — betterleaks rule id and line only, never the secret value;\n- author, actor kind (human|agent), and time;\n- a pointer to the review thread (the target entry id + the question-comment id).\n\nFor a NEW entry the quarantine item body IS the proposed body (the draft). For a\nheld update/patch/comment the item body renders the proposed change (new body,\ndiff, or comment text) for the reviewer; the payload op is stored so approval can\nreplay it exactly.\n\n## Write flow (all four surfaces, identical)\n\nA body/comment that trips betterleaks on a syncable target:\n\n- New entry (`kref_remember` / `kref new`): the draft is born in `quarantine`;\n  the review question-comment is anchored on the draft. Approve = `retier` the\n  draft to the intended tier (reuses the single movement verb).\n- Update / patch / comment on a live syncable entry: park the op as a quarantine\n  item; the live entry is untouched and stays syncable; anchor the review\n  question-comment on the LIVE target. Approve = replay the op onto the target.\n- Private (non-syncable) target: allowed as today, no quarantine (cannot push).\n- On park, the writer gets a clear result: `quarantined as \u003cid\u003e, pending human\n  review` naming the findings. An agent can then discuss in the thread.\n\nThe in-context review comment on a syncable target inherits the target's tier, so\nit will sync (it carries only rule+line metadata, never a secret) — collaborators\nsee that a local review is pending. The held payload and approve/reject stay\nhost-local (quarantine is a host-bound review gate, like other private-typed\ndata). This sync-visible-but-locally-actionable split is intended, not a leak.\n\n## Review and decision\n\n- `kref quarantine list` — pending items: id, target, findings, author, age.\n- `kref quarantine show \u003cid\u003e` — render the proposed body/diff/comment + findings.\n- Discuss in the target's thread: a reviewer asks \"fixture or live key?\", the\n  LLM author answers via `kref_comment`.\n- `kref quarantine approve \u003cid\u003e` — apply the op (or retier the draft), resolve\n  the thread, record who approved in provenance.\n- `kref quarantine reject \u003cid\u003e` — discard; preserve content to\n  `$XDG_STATE_HOME/kref/rejected/`; resolve the thread as rejected; tombstone\n  the item for audit.\n\n## --force = inline human approval\n\nA human at the CLI writing a fixture may pass `--force` to create AND approve the\nquarantine item atomically — audited through the same machinery, no two-step for\ntheir own content. MCP exposes no force; an LLM write always parks.\n\n## Surfaces and backstop\n\n- MCP gains a read-only `kref_quarantine` (list/show) so an agent can see its\n  parked write and answer in the thread. approve/reject stay human/CLI.\n- The push-time scan stays as defense-in-depth; push never ships the `quarantine`\n  namespace (non-syncable by construction). In steady state, live syncable\n  content is always approved-or-clean.\n- Pending count surfaces in the cockpit, `kref stats`, and the periodic nag.\n\n## Edge cases\n\n- Stale replay: approving a held UPDATE after the live target moved (e.g. a todo\n  whose version advanced) re-checks and fails with a clear conflict\n  (\"target moved vN-\u003evM since quarantine; re-review\") rather than clobbering.\n  Append-only comments never conflict.\n- Missing scanner: unchanged warn-not-fail; push still refuses unscanned syncable\n  content, so nothing leaves unscanned.\n- Reject disposition: content preserved to the recovery dir; item tombstoned\n  (auditable), not purged.\n\n## What this replaces\n\nThe refuse-and-preserve outcome becomes divert-to-quarantine. entryguard /\ncommentguard stay as the scan + policy core; their result changes from \"refuse\"\nto \"park in quarantine\". The human-only `--force` semantics change from\nscan-bypass to inline-approve. Net: a flagged write is never lost OR blocked\noutright — it is held for review.\n\n## Decomposition (build order)\n\nEach sub-project gets its own spec -\u003e plan -\u003e implementation cycle.\n\n- A — quarantine namespace + item model + park-on-write.\n  The reserved private-typed `quarantine` namespace; the quarantine-item entry\n  shape (parked op, target, findings, provenance); rewire entryguard/commentguard\n  outcomes from refuse to park across all four write surfaces (remember/update/\n  patch/comment, CLI + MCP). Deliverable: flagged writes land in quarantine with\n  their payload; nothing applies to the live target yet. Interface out: a stored\n  quarantine item addressable by id, plus the park result surfaced to the writer.\n\n- B — review + approve/reject + comment wiring.\n  Auto-open the in-context question-comment on the target/draft; `kref quarantine\n  approve|reject` (apply/replay or discard, resolve the thread, provenance);\n  `--force` = create+approve atomically; stale-replay conflict handling.\n  Depends on A (consumes the quarantine item + payload).\n\n- C — surfaces.\n  `kref quarantine list/show`; read-only MCP `kref_quarantine`; pending-count in\n  cockpit / `kref stats` / nag. Depends on A (item model) and reads B's state.\n\n## Open questions (defer to each sub-project's spec)\n\n- A: exact storage of the parked op — reuse the existing op payload types inside\n  the quarantine item body/metadata vs a dedicated parked-op record. Lean: store\n  the op payload so approval replays it verbatim.\n- A/B: whether the `quarantine` namespace is a full built-in tier (tier list /\n  retier targets) or a reserved non-tier ref-space with only retier-in/out. Lean:\n  a built-in private-typed tier hidden from listings, so `retier` promotion works\n  unchanged.\n- B: whether an agent may self-answer AND a human must still approve (yes), and\n  whether reject requires a note (lean: optional note, like resolve today).\n"},{"type":9,"timestamp":1784141427,"nonce":"fVI84xe2tf/0j8FSK9BMWaA8dHM=","label":"area:design"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1784141427,"nonce":"Mo62lz6djtxndqDJj75moJMhYoA=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_kind":"human","source_path":"","trigger":"create"},{"type":5,"timestamp":1784141467,"nonce":"C4ryQPqb8ZzLO7onKzZD5qy1aCg=","to":"81be409e4ef81864f5b3ca115375975cc3adc9ae256c44279148778c9506085e","link_type":"relates"},{"type":11,"timestamp":1784224332,"nonce":"3gLTt+TqYd2V8SYT7DLulB4kFT4=","actor":"Trevor Vaughan","actor_kind":"human","source_path":"","trigger":"retier"}]}